======================================================================
RANDOM SLOPES COMPARISON - RQ 5.2.3
======================================================================

PURPOSE: Test if individual differences in forgetting rate (random
         slopes on TSVR_hours) justify added model complexity.

TAXONOMY REQUIREMENT: Section 4.4 - Cannot claim homogeneous
                      effects without testing for heterogeneity

CONTEXT: Original analysis plan (2_plan.md) specified random slopes
         model but executed with intercepts-only due to convergence
         failure (summary.md lines 36-43). This script formally
         documents and validates that decision.

[STEP 1] Load LMM Input Data
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Loaded: 800 rows, 10 columns
Unique UIDs: 100
Domains: ['What', 'Where']
Tests per participant: 8.0

Model formula: Full 3-way Age × Domain × Time interaction
       (13 fixed effects terms with Linear+Log time effects)
       TSVR_hours (linear) + log_TSVR (logarithmic)

[STEP 2] Fit Model A: Random Intercepts Only (Current Implementation)
----------------------------------------------------------------------
This is the model currently used in results/summary.md

Model A converged: True
  Log-Likelihood: -760.64
  AIC: 1549.27
  BIC: 1614.86
  Random intercept variance: 0.3653
  Residual variance: 0.2903
  Observations: 800
  Groups: 100

[STEP 3] Fit Model B: Random Intercepts + Slopes for TSVR_hours
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Testing if individual differences in linear forgetting rate exist
This was the ORIGINAL plan specification (2_plan.md line 316)

Model B converged: False
  Log-Likelihood: -1154.88
  AIC: 2341.76
  BIC: 2416.71
  Random intercept variance: 0.7143
  Random slope variance: 0.1545
  Random slope SD: 0.3931
  Intercept-slope covariance: -0.0023
  Intercept-slope correlation: -0.007
  Residual variance: 0.1976
  Observations: 800
  Groups: 100

[STEP 4] Model Comparison via AIC
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Model A (Intercepts only):  AIC = 1549.27
Model B (Intercepts+Slopes): AIC = 2341.76
ΔAIC (A - B) = -792.49

ΔAIC = -792.49 < -2 → Model A (intercepts) preferred
         Slopes add complexity without improving fit

[STEP 5] Save Comparison Results
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Saved: /home/etai/projects/REMEMVR/results/ch5/5.2.3/data/step02_random_slopes_comparison.csv
Saved: /home/etai/projects/REMEMVR/results/ch5/5.2.3/results/step02_random_slopes_validation.md

======================================================================
Outcome: OPTION C SLOPES DONT IMPROVE
Interpretation: Random slope variance negligible, simpler model preferred
Recommendation: Use Model A (intercepts only). Homogeneous effects CONFIRMED.

Random slopes comparison complete

[TAXONOMY 4.4] Homogeneity hypothesis tested (convergence failure)
Intercepts-only model JUSTIFIED (data insufficient for slopes)
Documented in validation report
